<Rating>1< /Rating><name>Adam Young< /name>< review>
Describe my experience?

Well I stopped in to drop off a cable box that I never wanted to begin with but was forced to rent for the HD rollout. This is what the phone rep said I HAD to do to cancel my cable TV and said the changes to my plan would not occur until I did so.
So I arrive, really thinking it will be a couple minutes in and out. Turned out to be a 45min wait, maybe 50, and once I got to the counter it actually only took about 5 minutes.
My thought process is asking, why is there not a line or check in just for drop offs? First come first serve doesn't make a lot of sense when you have customers setting up new service and support questions taking extended periods of time and then people just dropping off equipment. Maybe have a line for drop offs and take other customers when no drop off customers are present? Maybe have a separate sign in and priority set to drop offs and pick-ups? Better yet, next time you can come by my house and pick your junk up yourselves.
Wait it gets better, so then I get home and my Internet is gone. I said I only wanted to cancel TV, I even have the router/modem equipment belonging to them at my house. If I were cancelling that also wouldn't I have had to turn in the modem also??? Instead of watching a movie I ended up sitting on the phone for an HOUR AND A HALF with 2 different techs resetting and troubleshooting the friggin Wi-Fi. The tech even said that the girl in the store sent out the wrong codes and messed everything up. Now I have over 2 hours of my Saturday wasted on a holiday weekend.
Wait, wait, wait, it gets even better, so apparently the Wi-Fi got "greyed out" or turned off on the modem. So now I have a tech coming to my house tomorrow at 1pm to replace the modem, no Internet until then and I work from home often and my fiance will miss Skyping overseas to her family, and I get to waste another half hour with some stranger in my house tomorrow. Fan-f $*#ing-tastic. Thanks Spectrum/Time Warner, you're the best.<//review>

<user_id>117961649017107274095<//user_id><name>Trevor B< /name><time>1601073340592< /time><Rating>1< /Rating>< review>
Update 9/25/20

I live in an area where the only option for internet is Spectrum because they have mafia-esque, anti-consumer rules in place dividing up the city amongst the largest ISP's in San Diego. They currently sell me 200mbit internet for $70/month. A block away, my neighbors can get 1000mbit for $40. New customers get a better deal, but Spectrum refuses to apply any deal to existing accounts. Today my upload rate was 0.9 mbps, despite the 10mbps (which sucks to begin with) upload rate I'm paying for.

Internet is a UTILITY that we NEED (especially during the pandemic when many of us are working from home), and we're dealing with non-compete agreements, under-performing service, and price gouging. Spectrum doesn't care either way as long as the money keeps flowing in.

----

Terrible customer service committed to wasting your time.

I had to spend over two hours on the phone setting up my account (the calls went to India, of course) only to find out the next day nobody had even created my account. Then they wanted me to wait for installers and pay a 15 dollar fee despite the fact I already owned all the required equipment. I called the fourth rep simply to see if reporting my Internet as out of service would allow me to circumvent this. It did. This lady allowed me to set everything up myself, and shipped me a DVR system.</review>

< Text>
I have been a regular to a dentist since the age of 4 and can recognize good dentists and a good clinic by the way they handle a situation and the way they treat you. Even though I live at a stone's throw distance from Dream smile dental, I got to know about their exceptional skill only recently when my wife needed some dental work.
The staff, Josh and Kristina, are very courteous and polite. they are knowledgeable about the treatment, insurance etc and not like the typical front-desk staff.
I had a filling that had fallen off and that I had kept open for a long time as I had gotten it done in India and my previous dentist had moved to a place that was no longer convenient to me. Shouldn't have kept it open, but lesson learned.
anyways, turned out that I needed a root canal. Dr. Dipali Dave did the initial analysis. She also gave me some additional suggestions. I love it when somebody can be realistic and work with your concerns rather than make it sound like a do or die situation.
I also needed some cleaning work. Jay, the hygienist, did the cleaning and he did a great job as well. Dr. Kruti Desai did my root canal treatment. She is very skillful and confident and knows exactly what she is doing.
Even though i have had a lot of 'dental experience', I loved the fact that all of them were gentle and often checking for any discomfort. I highly recommend Dream Smile Dental to individuals and families. You are in safe hands from the moment you set foot into the clinic.<//Text>

<rating>5<//rating>< Review>
Read for a thorough and honest review of SoCal Barber, a brand new barber shop serving the local Norwalk and Downey Community!

SoCal Barber needs to be your go-to barbershop in the Norwalk-Downey Community.  The owners opened their brand-new shop with a mission and passion to give the highest quality cuts to their customers.  I can attest that this shop will not disappoint, the customer service sets the highest standard of what competing barber shops should offer.  With more than seven seats and a talented barber to fill each one, you will never have to wait long and will leave looking your absolute freshest. With more than thirty combined years of barbershop experience, the owners strive to give the BEST cuts to their customers.

The shop is modern and welcoming; you immediately walk in to a row of brand new seats, husky toolboxes, and big screen TVs.  The magic is in the details as each barber apron adorns the SoCal logo.

SoCal Barber easily rates a 5 out of 5 for customer service, the owner has a motto that everyone should be treated as family; each customer is offered a bottle of water.

SoCal treats military and first responders very well

Bottom line or TLDR:  This is the best new barbershop in town.  I receive a high quality cut every single week, the price is competitive, the barbers are talented, and the customer service is on point.  Look no further, this is the one.

Overall score: 5 out of 5 : Perfect</Review>

< Text>
Awful experience. Actual fraud.

This gym appeared like the ideal gym to the point my wife and I decided to pay for personal training which is not cheap (obviously). We were offered a month trial to try it out and at the end we decided it wasn't for us. Well, seeking to cancel we were told we weren't allowed too. Come to find out, the person who got us to sign up was the training manager and he was engaging in fraud with another one of the trainers. Only he was fired (not the other one, whose name I wish I'd remember to rat him out too). Months went by due to the pandemic and payments started getting taken out of my bank. When I tried to get my refund I was told by the new manager that since I signed the document I was suppose to commit to the YEAR OF TRAINING. Apparently my wife and I weren't just fraudulently lured to a "month TRIAL", we were lured AND STILL ARE tied down to a YEAR CONTRACT. Over 1,000$ down the drain.

While I do want to make one thing clear, the three trainers who took turns training us were awesome, we have nothing but good things to say about them, our overall experience with the actual company was awful. The fact you can fire a manager for engaging in fraud, luring people like my wife and I to $1,000 dollar services, and then telling me because my signature is on the document that I can't cancel it is literally the definition of fraud. It's a breach of contract if I know any. Once more, the trainers were amazing and i'd recommend them to the world, but my issue is to corporate, or whoever runs the show in this place.

One last thing, I feel awful for the new manager who replaced the slime ball of the previous one because clearly she had to clean up the disgusting and expensive mess the previous manager left. She was amazing as well and I having nothing but great things to say about her as well, clearly her hands were tied because of the snakes up stairs. We were communicating with her for months because her superiors were taking forever to get back and kept telling her that if my signature was on the document I had to pull through with the entire contract. To my knowledge this manager who I'm referring to has now been replaced which probably means if I bring this up to her the same experience will resurface.I have 2 pending training services worth 170$. This place is so awful that I'm considering accounting that money as a sunk cost and never turning back.</Text>

<user>106579711042684843315<//user><user_name>June K<//user_name>< Time>
1578087221670<//Time>
<Rate>5< /Rate>< review>
Perfect location, friendly staff, neat facility with a cardio cinema and steam room! Parking is plenty around the building.

I signed up in October of 2019 since I moved to Murrieta and have since tried multiple group classes including Barr, Bodypump, pilates, yoga and more along with PT with Doulla. Variety of group classes keeps me engaged and having fun while exercising! As for PT, it was my first experience training with a trainer and I can't say enough good things about my trainer Doulla - she went through a thorough introductory session to identify the areas I needed to focus on and the core of my challenge, which is the hip tendonitis and customized a workout routine that works perfect for a weighlift beginner like myself, while reducing further injury. With her, I consider myself in great hands to get fitter and overcome injuries!

Also, I am grategul to Yusef for a great complementary welcome workout - the session was so much more than what I expected and it was what prompted me to sign up for the PT right away.

Overall, I love the gym. The only thing I hope for is maybe a bigger and cleaner restroom. The locker room is rather small and the showers are limited-only 3 for such a huge gym. Oh well, considering the services they provide and its price, it's a small problem that wouldn't deter me from continuing to enjoy this gym. I'd avoid the hours between 5 to 8 pm on weekdays if wants to avoid the crowds.</review>

Beware of them tricking you with their "promotions." The gym is currently offering a basic membership for 1 dollar down and 9.99 a month. But they will charge you a 39.99 dollar fee to lock in your rate. They don't tell you this in the advertisement and they do not tell you until you are about to sign the paper. This is a blatant lie and false advertising to potential clients. It is NOT $1down/$9.99permonth. It is either $41down/$9.99permonth or $1down/$14per month. <userid>112867865617212013800<//userid>< text>
I'm shocked at most of the negative reviews on this gym. I've been a member since the Gold's/EOS change over and I love it. I used to be a member of 24hr in Temecula and I must say that equipment breaks! I've been members of both (my wife is still at 24hr) and there are times when items are broken, its part of life. Usually at both gyms, the equipment is fixed in a day or so (no biggie). As for the rude staff, I will say that when I first signed up, there was one girl at the front desk that seemed to be bothered by anyone that came in the door, thankfully she's gone. but every morning I go in (usually around 5am), I'm always greeted by Lance (who knows my name) and I always get a "have a great workout" on my way in. When leaving, I always get the "have a great day!" This is a fairly small gym in comparison to the 24hr in Temecula and yes, its gets busy (I used to go at night), but if you can change your routine slightly, problem solved. Every morning there is free equipment to use, the staff is helpful and happy to answer questions. There is one guy that seems to think he's God's gift, but you know what... not everyone you come across in life is pleasant, so I know if I want to pay for a trainer, it AIN'T gonna be him! LOL. We started using Clark Pest Control almost immediately after moving to Modesto because of some weird looking bugs on the trees out back. The City eventually took out the trees to get rid of the bugs, but they still come back every summer.

When the bugs are doing their thing, Clark keeps them under control.< /Text>

<Pics>None< /Pics><Text>The only good thing about this place is the service. I remember why I haven't been there for over 8 years during my last visit.

1.  The rice to ingredient ratio in my sushi is 2 to 1. The sushi is enormous because they put so much rice in it. All you taste is rice not the other ingredients.

2.  I ordered tamago roll for my daughter and they decided to put lemon in it. Why???? That's the dumbest thing I've ever encountered.

3.  Conclusion is that it's not sushi chef making your sushi but people disguised as sushi chef and doesn't know what they are doing. You can make sushi but if you don't know why you should or shouldn't put in an ingredient, you're just a cook and not a chef.

I don't recommend this place if you're looking for a good Japanese meal. You won't be seeing me back.<//Text>< response>

<username>Kimberly Moore< /username><Time>1544260858525</Time></record></dataset><record>
< Text>
This is a very popular sushi restaurant with the locals.  Almost always full with a boisterous atmosphere.  The freshness of the seafood is good.  The teriyaki could be saucier but most come for the rolls.  So many to choose from from raw to fried to baked.  I like to pick up but if they say 40 minutes make it more like an hour on the busy nights.  If you make it there before your food is ready keep a diligent eye for your to-go bags because they may forget to call for you.  All in all pretty darn good Japanese food!</Text>

I ordered the sushi "to go" around 3:30 PM on Mon., April 12th, 2016. I had the Rainbow Roll and my Husband had the Spicy Tuna Roll. My Husband brought it back and it was HORRIBLE. <text>#Alotoffood. I enjoyed Sushi House! I was hungry and looking for a decent place with a good value. I came to the right place, because I won't go hungry eating here. I ordered a combo, but instantly wished that I went with sushi and rolls. It's a odd habit of mine. I always want some kind of meat and tempura with sushi as my side item. If only there was a way I could not get full on the the combo stuff and make roll for at least one roll. I guess I need to bring more people so we can share. I was so jealous when the table next to me ordered the Raider Roll! You know I represent, but I had way too much food in front of me to support the roll and my favorite team.

The parking situation can get a little crazy since it's on the corner of the shopping plaza, but I'm sure if you get there early for dinner this won't be problem. I was about to park near the front. The location near shoreline is the best part. This is a perfect for a date and affordable enough for the average college student.<//text>< username>

<Text>They have not mastered the covid-19 restaurant experience. The outdoor dining is literally painfully cold. I never complain about a place being too cold, but sushi House outdoor dining area is in an ice cavern. They have overhead heaters, but none of them were on. There's a cold wind blowing between a glass shield and the building.

Service is extremely slow. I understand that they are targeting the doordash and take out customers, but the service for both of them are also extremely slow.

Finally, what used to be a spicy tuna roll tonight was a tuna roll with a blob of sriracha sauce on top.part of what makes a spicy tuna roll tasty is that the tuna and Sriracha are mixed and refrigerated. A blob of sriracha makes for a uncomfortably spicy, poorly balanced tuna roll.

My two star review is a downgrade from what used to be a four star review for this restaurant. some restaurants have succeeded with the covid-19 procedures. But sushi House has not.<//Text></record>

Perfect time to visit and eat tonight, not crowded and not busy as it normally is, gives you a relaxing time to enjoy your meal.< /Text>

Mikee Solis</user_name>

</dataset><record>
<pictures>None<//pictures><time>1538063943354</time>< Text>
I give Sushi House a solid 3 stars, the sushi rolls were good, but not spectacular. The bento boxes were huge, the over all quality and quantity was definitely a good value for the price. For two people we had sushi rolls, bento boxes and soft drinks all for $77.

The menu is quite large, five pages. One page is nothing but pictures of all the sushi roll with the name listed under neeth. Great idea for anyone new to sushi.

For dinning out midweek, I was very suprized how busy it was. We didn't feel rushed, but the wait staff seemed to be overwhelmed. At one point I think I counted six sushi chef's behind the counter, but three or four wait staff to deal with well over fourty tables in the main dining area. This is most definitely a high volume establishment.

I was disappointed with the fact that they did not have any seared items, Like seared Ahi tuna. Also be prepared to take home left overs.

If you are new eating sushi or have never tried it but have wanted to Sushi House would be a good place to start.< /Text>

< time>
1340679017914< /time>
<Rating>4<//Rating>< Text>
Not the world's greatest sushi rolls, but they are HUGE. For under $40 for two, I can walk out of here absolutely stuffed (+1 for that because I usually walk out of sushi restaurants still hungry after dropping $100).

I think this place used to be a Coco's or something, and it still feels like it inside. The atmosphere is loud, a few tables look like fold-out card tables to squeeze more people in, and it almost has a cafeteria-like feel. I was expecting a food fight to break out at any time. But you do get a decent view of the water.

So go to get stuffed with mediocre sushi, but don't expect an upscale, top-notch sushi restaurant.</Text>

Not bad for sushi, but not the best. Sashimi tastes fresh and cut well, but the rolls are too large for each piece. The tolls aren't rolled tightly either so stuff just falls apart. They do, however, have a ton of special maki and temaki, as well as a few cooked sushi dishes, so it's a great place to introduce folks to sushi. We got the sushi yacht and 4 rolls for 6 people and it was way too much food. Still pretty good for a family place.< /Text>

< rating>
4< /rating>
<review>This place is reasonably close to my office, so I go here for lunch/dinner quite often. We also had a few company outings here. This is not really authentic Japanese restaurant. One of my Korean coworkers told me the place is owned by a Korean. The food is still quite delicious though (approved by one of my visiting Japanese coworker).

My favorite is the Sake Don. It's basically slices of salmon sashimi, tamago on a bed of sushi rice. They also give slices of lemon. Very fresh, very delicious, generous serving. What more can you ask?

As for the rolls, the serve several fusion dishes like baked scallion rolls. It's definitely different, definitely can't be found in Japan, but definitely good. Bring friends so you can share different varieties of rolls, or just bring a date and enjoy a short walk in the beach afterwards (bring layers, it can get pretty cold).< /review>< user>
108347904384031658715< /user>

<rating>3<//rating>< Review>
Bit of a disappointment here. Waited over an hour to eat mediocre sushi. The price was up there, but not the quality. Their sushi was ok but the temperature was off (almost room temperature). Oysters were nice and fresh but their $90.00 boat was mixed. We opted for the all sashimi option and most of the fish taste fresh but again the temperature of the sashimi was on the room temperature side.

Their rolls were a bit on the sloppy side and was ok.

Service here is spotty maybe because they're busy. It was also very room in the restaurant.

I miss Kamakura...< /Review>

<review>Love IT GREAT FOOD FRIENDLY SERVICE.</review></record></dataset><record>
<Pics>None< /Pics>< Date>
1404246999224< /Date>
<Text>I often go to Sushi House because it is close and affordable.  The wait for this restaurant is pretty long and it lasts late into the night.

I usually get the bimbibap salad which is a bed of salad greens tossed with chrysanthemum leaves and roughly chopped raw garlic and topped with sashimi (salmon, tuna, and tako).  They give a sweet and spicy Korean hot sauce so that people can customize the spiciness.  A bowl of rice is also provided to chow down this dish.  This is a delicious and refreshing dish although not always a hit because of the raw garlic and potential less than premium fish.

Everyone always raves about the Lion King Roll, which is pretty good, but not necessarily worth the almost $12 price tag.  The roll is a baked salmon roll with a sweet miso mayo sauce.  Tasty, but if you have tried it once, try something else on their extensive menu.

Also Sushi House is Korean owned and operated, not necessarily important, but if you are looking for authentic Japanese food this might not be that place.< /Text><GmapID>0x808f86a45a3d7401:0x50ee9025dc45fa4b< /GmapID><response>None< /response><userid>105715093055434905340< /userid><Rating>3< /Rating>< Name>
Sam S</Name>

<text>Bento box was amazing!< /text><user_id>104312584940167668870</user_id></record></dataset><record>
< Review>
I wanted to see the hype because it seems like Sushi House is famous, even for those not that familiar to Alameda.

I ordered the 2 item bento box with salmon terriyaki and tempura (1 piece of shrimp and a few veggies). My friends ordered a lion king roll and orange blossom roll, and the other ordered the katsu donburi. The bento box and katsu donburi come with soup and salad.

The sushi came out first. The orange blossom roll wasn't bad, the salmon wrapped around tasted fresh. But overall nothing impressive. The infamous lion king roll was fine. But definitely not rolled very well. Just picking it up it fell apart.

The katsu donburi bowl came out next. I didn't try any of it but my friend seemed unenthusiastic. She was picking around it, and the katsu looked soggy.

After about 20 min my box finally came out. The tempura was cold and bit soggy. The salmon was warm. It seemed like the entire time I was waiting for my box, my food was just sitting there. Meh.

The service was poor. Our waitress seemed rude and every time we asked for anything we'd get an eye roll. We didn't get spoons when she dropped off our soups (we just drank it from the bowl because we were starving) and then when my friend asked for a spoon for her katsu bowl, she handed her a plastic spoon. Seriously? There was a waitress that was going around filling waters and also cashed us out, she seemed nice though!

Do I see the hype? NOPE! There's better sushi places to eat in Alameda.</Review>

None</Pictures>
